chemical diffusion, allometric scaling, predator-prey relations, nerve impulses, and more. He presents Pearl’s causality calculus to resolve Simpson’s paradox, simple cardiac dynamics models, basic epidemiological models including Ronald Ross’s study of malaria and its epidemic curves, and limit cycles for the glycolysis model. Based on the author’s calculus class at Yale, the book makes concepts of calculus less abstract and more relatable for science majors and premedical students.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 21. Jun 2021) 0aLife sciencesxMathematical models. 7aMATHEMATICS / Applied.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2021 Englishz978311075400108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2021z9783110753776oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Mathematics 2021 Englishz978311075413108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Mathematics 2021z9783110753905oZDB-23-DMA08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertYale University Press Complete eBook-Package 2021z978311073923740uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780300258424423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780300258424.jpg  a978-3-11-073923-7  Yale University Press Complete eBook-Package 2021b2021  a978-3-11-075400-1  EBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2021 Englishb2021  a978-3-11-075413-1  EBOOK PACKAGE Mathematics 2021 Englishb2021  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-DGGb2021  aZDB-23-DMAb2021